*NF:* Well, it=E2=80=99s interesting. I think they were originally the Llam=
a team, and so I think they have a few things, they have the agility of a s=
tartup and I think that counts for a lot. Maybe they have some constraints =
that are helpful too. They have only so much capital, only so much compute,=
 and so they=E2=80=99re solving for those constraints.

*And maybe they can=E2=80=99t hire as many fine-tuners.*

*NF:* Right? Well, definitely not. It=E2=80=99s definitely the case that, o=
ne of the things that we talked about earlier that they care about deeply i=
s the quality of data and we know that they work very, very hard to clean t=
heir training data and to get effectively a compute multiplier out of doing=
 that, that gives them a quality multiplier. But right now they=E2=80=99re =
punching way above their weight and it feels almost like a magic trick. The=
ir new Mistral large model is performing really well on evals and they have=
n=E2=80=99t quite said what it is, maybe it=E2=80=99s an MOE mixture of Mis=
tral mediums or something like that. But my gosh, it=E2=80=99s really impre=
ssive and so yeah, I think there=E2=80=99s just a lot of agility there and =
a really hardcore team with great taste and great judgment that so far is m=
aking really great decisions.

*How do evals work, by the way? Everyone puts up these test numbers. What i=
s a good model? What is not?*

*NF:* Well, this is a funny topic, dear to my heart. It=E2=80=99s really fu=
nny to see, you have all these CEOs of all these companies that are trumpet=
ing their MMLU number ( https://paperswithcode.com/paper/measuring-massive-=
multitask-language ) and MMLU is an eval that Dan Hendrycks ( https://twitt=
er.com/danhendrycks ) developed himself when he was an undergrad. So you ha=
ve basically CEOs of trillion-dollar companies talking about their score on=
 an undergrad=E2=80=99s test, basically and this is the premier reasoning e=
val that=E2=80=99s out there.

I think if you just zoom way out and look at the progress in the AI field g=
enerally, we see incredible progress on models, incredible progress on alig=
nment tools like RLHF. Products finally feel like they=E2=80=99re really go=
ing, we=E2=80=99re seeing a lot of products, even policy people are really =
spun up. But the one progress bar that seems the furthest behind is evals, =
